```

Since the read operation at `/records/` is atomic, and there&#39;s no read rule that grants access to all of the data under `/records/`, this will throw a `PERMISSION_DENIED` error. If we evaluate this rule in the security simulator in our [Firebase console](//console.firebase.google.com/), we can see that the read operation was denied:

Attempt to read /records with auth=Success(null)
 /
 /records

No .read rule allowed the operation.
Read was denied.

The operation was denied because no read rule allowed access to the `/records/` path, but note that the rule for `rec1` was never evaluated because it wasn&#39;t in the path we requested. To fetch `rec1`, we would need to access it directly:

